{"questionId":"27676","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider a three-digit code <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>c</mi></math>, where each of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math> is assigned one of&nbsp;the values <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>c</mi></math>, where each of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi></math> is assigned one of&nbsp;the values <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>. Assume that no value is repeated.</p>\n<p>Consider the case where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> has a factor of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence show that the only way to assign the values is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;lead to invalid values for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mo>,</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>⇒</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp;so not possible&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;is the only solution&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>correctly argues <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> is the only possibility&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;is the only solution&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong></em><em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27676","referenceCode":"22N.1.AHL.TZ0.11b.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence show that the only way to assign the values is a=4, b=5 and c=2.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.3—Graphing","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.4—Key features of graphs, intersections using technology","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.12—Factor and remainder theorems, sum and product of roots"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}